      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0649P0-02565'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0649P0_20030616_GCR_117' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Clause 76 [<span class="italic">Second and empty homes: England</span>]:
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0649P0-02566'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0649P0_20030616_GCR_118' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        <span class="member">Lord Morgan</span> moved Amendment No. 154A:
        <q>Page 39, line 21, after "England" insert "and Wales</q>
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0649P0-02567'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0649P0_20030616_GCR_119' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        The noble Lord said: In moving Amendment No. 154A I shall speak also to Amendments Nos. 155A, 159A, 165A and, in Schedule 6, Amendments Nos. 228A to 228C. We believe that it is important that the provisions in Clause 76 being made for England should be extended to Wales.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0649P0-02568'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0649P0_20030616_GCR_120' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        The thrust of Clause 76 will allow English billing authorities to reduce or remove the 50 per cent discount which applies to dwellings with no residents for classes of dwellings prescribed in regulations made by the Secretary of State. Welsh local authorities already have power under Section 12 of the existing Local Government Finance Act 1992&#x2014;a Wales-only provision&#x2014;to reduce to 25 per cent or remove altogether the current 50 per cent discount for classes of unoccupied dwellings as prescribed by the Welsh Assembly.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0649P0-02569'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0649P0_20030616_GCR_121' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Clause 76 gives English authorities some additional flexibility over second and empty homes that is not included in the existing provision for Wales. Extending Clause 76 to Wales would allow the Welsh Assembly
        <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_202gc' title='Col. 202GC &mdash; HL Deb 16 June 2003 vol 649 c202GC' name='column_202gc' href='#column_202gc' rel='bookmark'>202GC</a>
        to prescribe classes of dwellings where a local authority could reduce the discount to amounts other than the 25 per cent or zero permitted under Section 12, and also to decide whether those discounts apply to the whole or part of a billing area to take account of its circumstances.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0649P0-02570'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0649P0_20030616_GCR_122' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        The proposals are supported by the Welsh Assembly and the Welsh Local Government Association. I trust, as does the noble Baroness, Lady Gale, that the amendments will be accepted by the Minister. It is important that the powers conferred by Clause 76 on English authorities should be at the disposal of Welsh authorities. I beg to move.
      </p>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0649P0-02571'>
        <a name='S5LV0649P0_20030616_GCR_123'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-jeff-rooker' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0649P0_20030616_GCR_123' title='Link to this speech by Mr Jeff Rooker' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-jeff-rooker" title="Mr Jeff Rooker">Lord Rooker</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            I have listened carefully to the comments made by my noble friend. The new power we propose for the English authorities provides greater flexibility than the current power, which the Welsh authorities have. Therefore, I am happy to agree to take away this set of amendments in the hope that I can return to this on Report, to see whether we can be positively helpful to our colleagues in the Welsh Assembly and give the Wales authorities the greater flexibility we are planning for England. In the light of that, I hope that the amendments will be withdrawn. I am extremely grateful for the issue being raised and shall return to this on Report.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
